---

Best Methods (ranked)

✅ 1. Logistic Regression with Odds Ratios (Highly Recommended)

Since features are one-hot encoded, logistic regression is excellent because coefficients are interpretable.

What to look at:

Positive coefficient = increases chance of target = 1

Negative coefficient = lowers chance

Larger absolute value = stronger predictor


Python:

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

X = df.drop(columns='target')
y = df['target']

model = LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced', max_iter=1000)
model.fit(X, y)

importance = pd.DataFrame({
    'feature': X.columns,
    'coef': model.coef_[0],
    'odds_ratio': np.exp(model.coef_[0])
})

importance.sort_values('coef', ascending=False)

Interpretation:

If:

Feature	Coef	Odds Ratio

feature_A	1.2	3.3


Then when feature_A = 1, odds of target=1 are 3.3x higher


---

✅ 2. Mutual Information (Nonlinear Strength)

Finds strongest relationship with target.

from sklearn.feature_selection import mutual_info_classif

mi = mutual_info_classif(X, y)

pd.DataFrame({
    'feature': X.columns,
    'mi_score': mi
}).sort_values('mi_score', ascending=False)

Good for ranking.


---

✅ 3. XGBoost / Random Forest Feature Importance

Captures interactions.

from xgboost import XGBClassifier

model = XGBClassifier(scale_pos_weight=18000/2700)
model.fit(X, y)

importance = pd.DataFrame({
    'feature': X.columns,
    'importance': model.feature_importances_
}).sort_values('importance', ascending=False)


